      "writtenOn": "2020-06-22T14:54:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "OK, this is an interesting concern. If someone calls \n  myString.resetToSize(100);\na.k.a.:\n  myString.resize(100);\na.k.a.:\n  myString.set(nullptr, 100);\n\nThen I expect the desired end state should be:\n  myString.size() is 100 (aka fRec-\u003efLength)\n  myString.c_str() is \"\" \n\nIn the previous code, the actual behavior would have been:\n  myString.size() is 100 (aka fRec-\u003efLength)\n  myString.c_str() may contain \"\"  *OR*\n  myString.c_str() may contain a truncated version of the previous\n                    contents, depending on string-uniqueness and prior length\n\nWhen you say \"forcing the length of the SkString back to zero\", do you mean fRec-\u003efLength? I don\u0027t think we want to zero that. That tracks our buffer size. We generally resetToSize right before populating the writable_str buffer via external means.\n\nA std::string would wipe its whole buffer on resize instead of just doing the quick first byte zero-termination. That\u0027s conceptually more pure, but I don\u0027t think that is the right tradeoff for us.",
      "parentUuid": "f4e5b5ba_7123ca4e",
      "revId": "b3833f72eacacc70e8b17afd59c591633869c981",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
